  "enhanced_information": "Lipids absorbed in the intestine are primarily transported to the liver by chylomicrons. Chylomicrons are formed in the intestinal cells after dietary fats are processed and are released into the lymphatic system before entering the bloodstream. They play a crucial role in transporting dietary lipids, including triglycerides, to various tissues, including the liver. The reasoning chains consistently support this process, confirming that chylomicrons are the main carriers of lipids from the intestine to the liver. Other lipoproteins like VLDL, HDL, and LDL are involved in lipid transport but are not responsible for the initial transfer of dietary lipids from the intestine to the liver."
